Three steps to becoming your students’ families’ favorite teacher! 1- Learn from them! Family input surveys are a great way to get more information about your student, and it shows you value their input. 2- Communication is key! Apps like @classtagme (#ad) allow you to stay in contact easily and securely. And finally 3- Make sure families know they’re an important part of their child’s academic team.  As you begin the new school year, make sure you build those relationships from the start!
.
.

Let me show you three different ways I differentiate the same assignment. This erasable highlighter from Frixion is one of my favorite tools in my classroom. I can mark on the papers and then erase and do it again if I need to. And graphic organizers aren’t just for writing. I love this one for math to help the students with area model. Each student gets the same paper, but each paper is changed just a little bit to meet each of their needs.
.
.
.

First #feetupfriday of the new school year. I started my new digital sped binder for my new caseload. I read the IEPs I currently have access to. I was trained on two new instructional programs. I hung decorations. And now, it’s time to mentally prepare. One more work day Monday and then kids come back and it’s time to dive into learning! It was the shortest summer ever (literally- only 8 weeks), but I’m excited to meet my new favorite students and see some old favorites, too. How much do you have left of your summer?
.
.
.

node.text:
Four years ago, I left my comfort zone. I left everything I had ever done in order to step into a new role. I gave up my previous tenured position to pursue my dream of being a special education teacher. And today, I earned that tenure back while living out my passion for sped in the role of a lifetime. The last three years have brought wisdom and humility and praise and tears. They have brought me some of the most incredible opportunities, amazing friends, and the best students. And to think I almost let all of this pass me by in favor of being “comfortable.” So please, take this as your sign that it’s never too late to go after your dreams, and then when you reach them, DREAM BIGGER!
.
.
.

And it keeps our messages secure and even translates them into the families' native languages automatically. Click the link in my bio and head to @classtagme for more info

node.text:
Do you give your personal number to parents? That question always seems to come up in my meetings and when I'm talking to new teachers. We want our students' families to be able to get in touch, but we don't want to cross that professional line. #ad This year, I am excited to partner with @classtagme to ensure effective two-way communication with my families without giving them full access to my personal life. Plus, @classtagme offers a much more inclusive platform than texting. #Iloveclasstagbecause it allows my non-English speaking families the ability to have messages instantly translated into their native language so we can make sure no information is getting lost. My personal cell phone can't do that. So head over to @classtagme or click the link in my bio to sign up and find out more.
.
.
.
